T1  - Income Distribution, Product Quality, and International Trade
AU  - Fajgelbaum, Pablo
AU  - Grossman, Gene M.
AU  - Helpman, Elhanan
Y1  - 2011/08/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/662628
DO  - 10.1086/662628
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 721
EP  - 765
VL  - 119
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We develop a framework for studying trade in horizontally and vertically differentiated products. In our model, consumers with heterogeneous incomes and tastes purchase a homogeneous good and make a discrete choice of quality and variety of a differentiated product. The distribution of preferences generates a nested-logit demand structure such that the fraction of consumers who buy a higher-quality product rises with income. The model features a home-market effect that helps to explain why richer countries export higher-quality goods. It provides a tractable tool for studying the welfare consequences of trade and trade policy for different income groups in an economy.
AB  - We develop a framework for studying trade in horizontally and vertically differentiated products. In our model, consumers with heterogeneous incomes and tastes purchase a homogeneous good and make a discrete choice of quality and variety of a differentiated product. The distribution of preferences generates a nested-logit demand structure such that the fraction of consumers who buy a higher-quality product rises with income. The model features a home-market effect that helps to explain why richer countries export higher-quality goods. It provides a tractable tool for studying the welfare consequences of trade and trade policy for different income groups in an economy.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/662628
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/662628
Y2  - 2024/03/20
